05112nam a22006375i 9780674259034DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20212021mau    fo  d z      eng d  a97806742590347 a10.4159/97806742590342doi  a(DE-B1597)583135  a(OCoLC)1251175126  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  amaucUS-MA 4aQA76.9.I52 7aSCI0340002bisacsh04a001.4/2262231 aFriendly, Michael, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut12aA History of Data Visualization and Graphic Communication /cHoward Wainer, Michael Friendly. 1aCambridge, MA : bHarvard University Press, c[2021] 4c©2021  a1 online resource (288 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- t1 In the Beginning . . . -- t2 The First Graph Got It Right -- t3 The Birth of Data -- t4 Vital Statistics: William Farr, John Snow, and Cholera -- t5 The Big Bang William Playfair, the Father of Modern Graphics -- t6 The Origin and Development of the Scatterplot -- t7 The Golden Age of Statistical Graphics -- t8 Escaping Flatland -- t9 Visualizing Time and Space -- t10 Graphs as Poetry -- tLearning More -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tAcknowledgments -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aA comprehensive history of data visualization—its origins, rise, and effects on the ways we think about and solve problems. With complex information everywhere, graphics have become indispensable to our daily lives. Navigation apps show real-time, interactive traffic data. A color-coded map of exit polls details election balloting down to the county level. Charts communicate stock market trends, government spending, and the dangers of epidemics. A History of Data Visualization and Graphic Communication tells the story of how graphics left the exclusive confines of scientific research and became ubiquitous. As data visualization spread, it changed the way we think. Michael Friendly and Howard Wainer take us back to the beginnings of graphic communication in the mid-seventeenth century, when the Dutch cartographer Michael Florent van Langren created the first chart of statistical data, which showed estimates of the distance from Rome to Toledo. By 1786 William Playfair had invented the line graph and bar chart to explain trade imports and exports. In the nineteenth century, the “golden age” of data display, graphics found new uses in tracking disease outbreaks and understanding social issues. Friendly and Wainer make the case that the explosion in graphical communication both reinforced and was advanced by a cognitive revolution: visual thinking. Across disciplines, people realized that information could be conveyed more effectively by visual displays than by words or tables of numbers. Through stories and illustrations, A History of Data Visualization and Graphic Communication details the 400-year evolution of an intellectual framework that has become essential to both science and society at large.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aGraphic methodsxHistory. 0aInformation visualizationxHistory. 0aVisual analyticsxHistory. 0aVisual communicationxHistory. 7aSCIENCE / History.2bisacsh1 aWainer, Howard, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021 Englishz978311075400108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021z9783110753776oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2021 Englishz978311075408708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2021z9783110753851oZDB-23-DEG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHarvard University Press Com